docs.lead_paragraph: From the government shutdown to the defense secretary’s resignation, it’s been a busy week in American politics. Here are some of the biggest stories you might have missed (and some links if you’d like to read further).

headline.main: On Politics: The Biggest Stories of the Week

docs.abstract: Indicating that he wanted to help fix a dysfunctional Senate, Mr. Merkley said there were other Democrats in the race who recognized the challenges ahead.
docs.snippet: Indicating that he wanted to help fix a dysfunctional Senate, Mr. Merkley said there were other Democrats in the race who recognized the challenges ahead.
docs.lead_paragraph: Jeff Merkley, a two-term senator from Oregon, has opted out of running for the 2020 presidential nomination, forgoing what would have been a long-shot bid against some of the most famous names in Democratic politics. He said he would instead pursue re-election to the Senate.

headline.main: Jeff Merkley, Oregon Senator, Says He Won’t Run for President
headline.print_headline: Progressive to Seek Re-election In Senate Over Presidential Bid

docs.abstract: The technology is feasible for a Green New Deal, though experts doubt its goals could be accomplished as quickly as advocates hope. Finding money and political will is a bigger challenge.
docs.snippet: The technology is feasible for a Green New Deal, though experts doubt its goals could be accomplished as quickly as advocates hope. Finding money and political will is a bigger challenge.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump derided the Green New Deal as a “high school term paper that got a low mark.” Congressional Republicans mocked it as “zany.” Even Nancy Pelosi, the Democratic House speaker, called the proposal a “green dream,” and some of the party’s 2020 candidates are starting to describe it as merely aspirational.

headline.main: A Green New Deal Is Technologically Possible. Its Political Prospects Are Another Question.
headline.print_headline: A New Deal at Once Possible and Problematic

byline.original: By Lisa Friedman and Trip Gabriel

docs.abstract: The New York Times sent a climate policy survey to the 18 declared candidates. They all want to stick to the Paris Agreement. Beyond that, they diverge.
docs.snippet: The New York Times sent a climate policy survey to the 18 declared candidates. They all want to stick to the Paris Agreement. Beyond that, they diverge.
docs.lead_paragraph: For Democrats vying to unseat President Trump, acknowledging climate change is easy. Deciding what to do about it is the hard part.

headline.main: We Asked the 2020 Democrats About Climate Change (Yes, All of Them). Here Are Their Ideas.
headline.print_headline: What Ought to Be Done About Climate Change? Let’s Ask the Candidates

docs.abstract: The former housing secretary in the Obama administration and the former mayor of San Antonio announced he was forming a presidential exploratory committee.
docs.snippet: The former housing secretary in the Obama administration and the former mayor of San Antonio announced he was forming a presidential exploratory committee.
docs.lead_paragraph: HOUSTON — Julián Castro, the former housing secretary in the Obama administration and the former mayor of San Antonio, announced on Wednesday that he was forming a presidential exploratory committee, the first potential step toward a bid for the White House in 2020.

headline.main: Julián Castro, Former Housing Secretary, Takes Step Toward a Presidential Run

docs.abstract: Black voters, disappointed by 2016, are carefully scrutinizing potential Democratic presidential candidates.
docs.snippet: Black voters, disappointed by 2016, are carefully scrutinizing potential Democratic presidential candidates.
docs.lead_paragraph: BALTIMORE — The first “Amen!” rang out after a couple of minutes, as Senator Elizabeth Warren, speaking to an almost all-black audience at Morgan State University’s winter commencement, described how America has “systematically discriminated against black people.”

headline.main: Black Voters, a Force in Democratic Politics, Are Ready to Make Themselves Heard
headline.print_headline: For 2020 Nominee, Black Voters Demand More

docs.abstract: Senator Warren, a Massachusetts Democrat, said she was forming a presidential exploratory committee, which allows her to raise money and hire staff before a formal kickoff.
docs.snippet: Senator Warren, a Massachusetts Democrat, said she was forming a presidential exploratory committee, which allows her to raise money and hire staff before a formal kickoff.
docs.lead_paragraph: Senator Elizabeth Warren, the Massachusetts Democrat and a sharp critic of big banks and unregulated capitalism, entered the 2020 race for president on Monday, becoming the first major candidate in what is likely to be a long and crowded primary marked by ideological and generational divisions in a Democratic Party determined to beat President Trump.

headline.main: Elizabeth Warren Announces Iowa Trip as She Starts Running for President in 2020
headline.print_headline: Warren Declares Presidential Bid To Unseat Trump

byline.original: By Astead W. Herndon and Alexander Burns

docs.abstract: Democrats are in a moment of transition, grappling with what they stand for and what their voters expect. Hardly any of their likely candidates for 2020 qualify as an instant front-runner.
docs.snippet: Democrats are in a moment of transition, grappling with what they stand for and what their voters expect. Hardly any of their likely candidates for 2020 qualify as an instant front-runner.
docs.lead_paragraph: Senator Elizabeth Warren’s formation of an exploratory committee for president on Monday represents a sort of political ball drop, the beginning of a new year and new campaign that will feature an unusually large number of Democrats seeking the presidency.

headline.main: 2020 Candidates Are Lining Up. Which Democrat Matches the Moment?
headline.print_headline: Democratic Hopefuls Are Lining Up, but Who Matches the Moment?

byline.original: By Jonathan Martin and Alexander Burns

docs.abstract: Democrats will move quickly to try to build grass-roots support and raise money — two prerequisites for any candidate hoping to break out of what is likely to be a congested pack of contenders.
docs.snippet: Democrats will move quickly to try to build grass-roots support and raise money — two prerequisites for any candidate hoping to break out of what is likely to be a congested pack of contenders.
docs.lead_paragraph: The new year has begun, and so has the nomination process for next year’s presidential election. But what do candidates actually do at this point, when the Iowa caucuses are still 13 months away?

headline.main: Five Ways Elizabeth Warren (and Other 2020 Hopefuls) Will Campaign When There’s No Campaign Yet
headline.print_headline: Five Ways to Campaign Before the Campaign Really Gets Rolling
